{
  "Triage Note (1300)": "A 68-year-old male with a history of CKD stage 4, HTN, and HFpEF presents to the ED with a 2-day history of progressive muscle weakness, fatigue, and nausea. Client states he has been taking 'some extra ibuprofen' for worsening knee pain. Reports running out of his furosemide 3 days ago but has continued his other prescribed medications. He mentions he has been unable to afford the copay for physical therapy for his knee osteoarthritis.",
  "ED Nurse Note (1430)": "Client is lethargic but oriented to person and place. Denies chest pain or shortness of breath. Bilateral lower extremity muscle strength is 3/5. Abdomen is soft, non-distended with hypoactive bowel sounds. Skin is cool and pale."
}

{
  "12-Lead ECG Interpretation (1415)": "Sinus bradycardia at 52 bpm. Prominent peaked T waves noted in precordial leads. PR interval prolonged (0.24 seconds). QRS complex widened (0.14 seconds). Findings are highly suggestive of severe hyperkalemia."
}

